05/09/2004
SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- BiH Prime Minister Adnan Terzic and Serbia-Montenegro Minister for Human and Minority Rights Rasim Ljajic held talks Friday (3 September) on how to improve bilateral co-operation in apprehending war crimes suspects. They agreed that the exchange of information between that the two countries' border services should be enhanced. Lajic, who also heads Serbia-Montenegro's national council for co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal, said Belgrade was willing to intensify collaboration with The Hague. 
In other news, BiH authorities have reportedly been investigating a Sarajevo-based firm said to be co-owned by a Saudi businessman, Yassin Al-Kadi, whose name has been linked to al-Qaeda. In separate articles, the Banja Luka daily <I>Nezavisne novine</I> and Zagreb's <I>Vecernji list</I> reported that police are conducting a probe to determine whether the company Risala was used for money laundering and financing of terrorist organisations. (Nezavisne novine, Vecernji list, Daily News - 04/09/04; PBS BiH, Fena - 03/09/04) 
